# DevOpsify

> One command. Full production DevOps setup around any GitHub repo.

Built by **Jayvardhan Singh Negi**

---

## What It Does

DevOpsify takes any Python or Node.js GitHub repo and automatically:

1. Clones the repo
2. Detects language, port, entry point, secrets, and DB dependencies
3. Generates a complete DevOps setup around it:
   - Multi-stage Dockerfile
   - Kubernetes manifests (Deployment, Service, Ingress, HPA, ConfigMap)
   - Prometheus + Grafana monitoring
   - Terraform infrastructure (EKS, ECR, VPC, IAM)
   - GitHub Actions CI/CD pipeline
4. Deploys it — to minikube locally or AWS EKS via `--cloud`
5. Shows you the live URL
6. Auto-destroys everything after your confirmation

---

## Requirements

### Required on your machine

| Tool | Version | Install |
|---|---|---|
| Python | 3.10+ | pre-installed |
| Docker | any | [docs.docker.com](https://docs.docker.com/get-docker/) |
| Git | any | pre-installed |
| minikube | latest | [minikube.sigs.k8s.io](https://minikube.sigs.k8s.io/docs/start/) |
| kubectl | latest | [kubernetes.io](https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/tools/) |

### For `--cloud` only

| Tool | Install |
|---|---|
| Terraform | [developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/install](https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/install) |
| AWS CLI | [aws.amazon.com/cli](https://aws.amazon.com/cli/) |

### Install minikube + kubectl on Mac M1

```bash
brew install minikube
brew install kubectl
```

---

## Installation

```bash
git clone https://github.com/jayvardhan/devopsify
cd devopsify
pip install -e .
```

Verify:

```bash
devopsify --help
```

---

## Usage

### Basic (minikube)

```bash
devopsify deploy --repo https://github.com/<user>/<repo>
```

### Cloud (AWS EKS)

```bash
devopsify deploy --repo https://github.com/<user>/<repo> --cloud
```

### Private repo

```bash
devopsify deploy --repo https://github.com/<user>/<private-repo>
# DevOpsify will ask if it's private and prompt for your GitHub token
```

### Skip the repo prompt

```bash
devopsify deploy --repo https://github.com/<user>/<repo>
```

---

## Interactive Flow

When you run `devopsify deploy`, it walks you through:

```
1. GitHub repo URL
2. Is it private? (token prompt if yes)
3. Clone + auto-detect
4. Show detection summary → confirm
5. App name
6. CPU + Memory (with helper guide)
7. Secret values from .env.example (hidden input)
8. DB notice if detected
9. Confirm deploy target
10. Generate all files → devopsified-output/<app-name>/
11. Deploy
12. Show live URL + Grafana link
13. Press Enter to auto-destroy
14. Everything cleaned up
```

---

## Resource Guide

When prompted for CPU and memory:

```
Small app  (portfolio, todo, landing page) → 250m  CPU, 256Mi RAM
Medium app (REST API, dashboard, scraper)  → 500m  CPU, 512Mi RAM
Heavy app  (ML model, video, data pipeline)→ 1000m CPU, 1Gi   RAM
```

---

## Generated Output

```
devopsified-output/
└── <app-name>/
    ├── Dockerfile
    ├── docker-compose.yml
    ├── README.md
    ├── k8s/
    │   ├── deployment.yaml
    │   ├── service.yaml
    │   ├── ingress.yaml
    │   ├── hpa.yaml
    │   ├── configmap.yaml
    │   └── monitoring/
    │       ├── prometheus.yaml
    │       └── grafana.yaml
    ├── terraform/
    │   ├── main.tf
    │   ├── variables.tf
    │   ├── vpc.tf
    │   ├── eks.tf
    │   └── ecr.tf
    └── .github/
        └── workflows/
            └── deploy.yml
```

